    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3614340292" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3614340292" />
    <a title="Kelly Brill" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3026432-kelly-brill"><img alt="Kelly Brill" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1404940391p2/3026432.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3614340292?book_show_action=true">Oct 26, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kelly Brill" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kelly Brill" href="/user/show/3026432-kelly-brill">Kelly Brill</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780805050875" href="/book/show/105614.An_Interrupted_Life">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3614340292" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7592593868995743291">I had heard the name Etty Hillesum for some time; her story was very vague in the back of my mind. Finally this fall I purchased her book of letters and diaries and am grateful for it. Grateful that she wrote, grateful that her words were preserved, grateful for a legacy of strength in the face of terror and horror.<br/><br/>Etty Hillesum was a 27-year-old Jewish woman living in Amsterdam when she wrote these journals - they cover the years 1941 and 1942. The letters are written from the Westerbork transp</span>
  <span id="freeText7592593868995743291" style="display:none">I had heard the name Etty Hillesum for some time; her story was very vague in the back of my mind. Finally this fall I purchased her book of letters and diaries and am grateful for it. Grateful that she wrote, grateful that her words were preserved, grateful for a legacy of strength in the face of terror and horror.<br /><br />Etty Hillesum was a 27-year-old Jewish woman living in Amsterdam when she wrote these journals - they cover the years 1941 and 1942. The letters are written from the Westerbork transport camp in 1943.<br /><br />Reading Etty’s journals, I was fascinated by the way in which she attended to the development of her own inner life (reflecting on what she was learning, writing, working on, and her relationships) while at the same time aware…more so with every month…that her outer life would soon be dramatically, drastically changing. She writes about the camps, the roundups of people by the Nazis with an inevitability that is at times chilling. Her writings are not very political - I don’t believe she mentions Hitler’s name. <br /><br />From the foreword: “…her most intense need, and gift, was for the inner life.” “She had become exquisitely attuned to the currents of moral beauty, and she could not bear the ugliness that was flooding the world.”<br /><br />The introduction of the book calls her narrative a “counterscenario,” not because she changed the course of events, obviously, but because 1941 and 1942 were, for her, a time of personal growth and liberation. (The Nazis couldn’t take that away.). Reminiscent of the much-younger Anne Frank, she writes, “Despite everything, life is full of beauty and meaning.”<br /><br />A few of my highlights from her journals:<br />	“…indiscriminate hatred is the worst thing there is. It is a sickness of the soul. Hatred does not lie in my nature.” She is observant of nature, sometimes with the present awareness that she will not always have it accessible around her: “I felt that God’s world was beautiful despite everything, but its beauty now filled me with joy.”<br />	“To live fully, outwardly and inwardly, not to ignore external reality for the sake of the inner life, or the reverse - that’s quite a task…And tomorrow back to work: studying, housekeeping, and working on myself, nothing must be neglected, and don’t take yourself too seriously either; and now goodnight.”<br />	“…you must remain your own witness, marking well everything that happens in this world…You must come to grips with these terrible times and try to find answers to the many questions they pose.”<br /><br />Her spirituality is very ecumenical; she does not appear to be a religiously observant Jew. One day she finds herself on her knees praying, “I am a kneeler in training.” She remembers a conversation she had with Julius Spier (I won’t describe that relationship here!) in which one of his patients said to him, “I sometimes have the feeling that God is right inside me, for instance when I hear the Saint Matthew Passion.” Spier commented, “At such moments you are completely at one with the creative and cosmic forces that are at work in every human being.” (My note: the cosmic Christ?)<br /><br />	One morning she opens her Bible and receives…”enormous faith and gratitude that life should be so beautiful, and that makes this a historic moment, that and not the fact that S. and I are on our way to the Gestapo this morning.”<br /><br />“How rash to assert that man shapes his own destiny. All he can do is determine his inner responses. You cannot know another’s inner life from his circumstances. To know that you must know his dreams, his relationships, his moods, his disappointments, his sickness, and his death.”<br /><br />She described an encounter with a disgruntled young Gestapo officer. Her reaction seems as if it could have been written today, (sadly): “…pitiful young men like that are dangerous as soon as they are let loose on mankind.”<br /><br />Contemplating her fate and that of most of her friends and relatives: “If you have a rich inner life…there probably isn’t all that much difference between the inside and outside of a camp…Life is going to be very hard. We shall be torn apart, all who are dear to one another. I don’t think the time is very far off now. We shall have to steel ourselves inwardly more and more.”<br /><br />I don’t see any evidence that she ever read any Buddhism, but her approach seems Buddhist sometimes…she writes about moments of agony that pass through her…she does not cling to them…”With each minute that passes I shed more wishes and desires and attachments.”<br /><br />A long quote that I find quite extraordinary:<br />	“Yes, life is beautiful, and I value it anew at the end of every day, even though I know that the sons of mothers, and you are one such mother, are being murdered in concentration camps.  And you must be able to bear your sorrow; even if it seems to crush you, you mustn’t run away from it, but bear it like an adult.  Do not relieve your feelings through hatred, do not seek to be avenged on all German mothers, for they, too, sorrow at this very moment for their slain and murdered sons.  Give your sorrow all the space and shelter in yourself that is its due, for if everyone bears his grief honestly and courageously, the sorrow that now fills the world will abate.  But if you do not clear a decent shelter for your sorrow, and instead reserve most of the space inside you for hatred and thoughts of revenge — from which new sorrows will be born for others — then sorrow will never cease in this world and will multiply.  And if you have given sorrow the space its gentle origins demand, then you may truly say: life is beautiful and so rich.  So beautiful and so rich that it makes you want to believe in God.”<br /><br />“…even as we die a terrible death we are able to feel right up to the very last moment that life has meaning and beauty, that we have realized our potential and lived a good life. I can’t really put it into words.” (Oh, but she did!)<br /><br />Someone told her once, “You live too cerebral a life”…but she realized later “with ever-greater certainty: he wasn’t right. True, I may think too much, sometimes with a demonic and ecstatic intensity, but I refresh myself from day to day at the original source, life itself, and I rest from time to time in prayer. And what those who say ‘You live too intensely’ do not know if that one can withdraw into a prayer as into a convent cell and leave again with renewed strength and with peace regained.”<br /><br />I have heard that some have criticized Etty for not being involved in the resistance or not trying to resist or hide herself. Her own resistance was interior. “Ultimately, we have just one moral duty: to reclaim large areas of peace in ourselves, more and more peace, and to reflect it toward others. And the more peace there is in us, the more peace there will also be in our troubled world.”<br /><br />Letters from Westerbork:<br />	Most of her letters describe the situation at camp, the lack of sanitation, the terrible food - she writes apologetically but directly as she asks her friends to send packages — almost entirely for her parents. These letters are full of empathy and no self-pity. Still she writes that she still maintains “like some elementary force - the feeling that life is glorious and magnificent, and that one day we shall be building a whole new world. Against every new outrage and every fresh horror, we shall put up one more piece of love and goodness, drawing strength from within ourselves.” She continues to see beauty in “even the places that geography books describe as barren and dull.”<br /><br />To her friend Tide, she sends this prayer from her diary: <br />	“You have made me so rich, oh God, pleas let me share out Your beauty with open hands. My life has become an uninterrupted dialogue with You, oh God, one great dialogue. Sometimes when I stand in some corner of the camp, my feet planted on Your earth, my eyes raised toward Your heaven, tears sometimes run down my face, tears of deep emotion and gratitude. At night, too, when I lie in my bed and rest in You, oh God, tears of gratitude run down my face, and that is my prayer. I have been terribly tired for several days, but that too will pass. Things come and go in a deeper rhythm, and people must be taught to listen; it is the most important thing we have to learn in his life. I am not challenging You, oh God, my life is one great dialogue with You. I may never become the great artist I would really like to be, but I am already secure in You, God…all my creative power are translated into inner dialogues with You. The beat of my heart has grown deeper, more active, and yet more peaceful, and it is as if I were all the time sorting up inner riches.”</span>
  <a data-text-id="7592593868995743291" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


