<span id="freeTextContainer14698978589791078412">The edition I read didn’t come up on the list. Mine is published by Persephone and has letters in the back written when in the concentration camp. <br/><br/>This is a difficult book to wade through. I wanted to really like it but found the start dense and naval gazing in the way adolescents have. I became angry at the behaviour of her psychoanalyst with whom she was enthralled and his boundaries may have been of the time but to a modern eye they were abusive. Slowly tiny bits of Natzi oppression of the Je</span>
  <span id="freeText14698978589791078412" style="display:none">The edition I read didn’t come up on the list. Mine is published by Persephone and has letters in the back written when in the concentration camp. <br /><br />This is a difficult book to wade through. I wanted to really like it but found the start dense and naval gazing in the way adolescents have. I became angry at the behaviour of her psychoanalyst with whom she was enthralled and his boundaries may have been of the time but to a modern eye they were abusive. Slowly tiny bits of Natzi oppression of the Jews starts and engages the reader but very slowly as though Etty is living in a bubble. There is no doubting her courage and kindness in the most awful of circumstances. This is not an autobiography it is a snapshot of one young woman’s internal world and musings at a time of gruesome upheaval. I’m sorry I didn’t like it more. </span>
